# regular expression
def clean(text):
    
    text = re.sub(r'[^A-Za-z0-9]+', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\d\w*', ' ', text)
    return text
    
transaction_data['PROD_NAME'] =transaction_data['PROD_NAME'].apply(clean)

In [752]:
#define a function to combine same brand
def clean_brand(data):
        x=data['Brands']
        if x=='Natural' or x=='NCC':
            return 'Natural Chip Co.'
        elif x =='Dorito':
            return 'Doritos'
        elif x =='Grain':
            return 'GrnWves'
        elif x =='Infzns':
            return 'Infuzions'
        elif x =='Red':
            return 'RRD'   
        elif x =='Smith':
            return 'Smiths'
        elif x =='Snbts':
            return 'Sunbites'
        elif x =='WW':
            return 'Woolworths'
        else:
            return x
        
transaction_data["Brands"] = transaction_data.apply(lambda data: clean_brand(data), axis=1)

T-test¶

In [471]:
#Perform an independent t-test between mainstream vs premium and budget midage and young singles and couples

mainstream = df_merge["PREMIUM_CUSTOMER"] == "Mainstream"
young_midage = (df_merge["LIFESTAGE"] == "MIDAGE SINGLES/COUPLES") | (df_merge["LIFESTAGE"] == "YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES")

non_mainstream = (df_merge["PREMIUM_CUSTOMER"] == "Budget") | (df_merge["PREMIUM_CUSTOMER"] == "Premium")

a = df_merge[young_midage & mainstream]["TOT_SALES"]
b = df_merge[young_midage & non_mainstream]["TOT_SALES"]
res= ttest_ind(a.values, b.values, equal_var=False)
print(res)
Out[471]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=33.06748508665193, pvalue=1.834645908183037e-237)

The t-test results in a p-value of 1.834645908183037e-237 which less than 0.05. It reject the null hypothesis and as t = 33.0674 . the unit price for mainstream,young and midage singles and couples ARE significantly higher than that of budget or premium, young and midage singles and couples.

4. Affinity analysis¶

We might want to target customer segments that contribute the most to sales to retain them or further increase sales. I would target Mainstream - young singles/couples to see if they tend to buy a particular brand of chips.
